                        <p>Flood insurance covers losses directly caused by flooding. Flood insurance is specific to flooding since most homeowners insurance does not cover flood damage.</p>

                        <h4>What is a flood?</h4>

                        <p>In simple terms, a flood is an excess of water on land that is normally dry, affecting two or more acres of land or two or more properties. For example, damage caused by a sewer backup is covered if the backup is a direct result of flooding. <a class="usa-link" href="https://agents.floodsmart.gov/sites/default/files/fema_nfip-summary-coverage-brochure-12-2023.pdf">Official Definition of a flood</a>. </p>

                        <h4>What is covered?</h4>

                        <p>In the event of a flood, your National Flood Insurance Program (NFIP) policy covers direct physical losses to your structure and belongings.</p>
                        <p>The NFIP offers two types of coverage; building coverage and contents coverage.</p>
                        <p>There are many circumstances that factor into what is covered, such as where you live, the kind of house you live in, the age of your home, and how it's built and arranged. Below are links to learn more.</p>

